column169: attachment Name:IMG_7367.JPG

On October 23, 2024, an incident occurred at Veolia's ten-day in-transit facility located in Menomonee Falls, Wisconsin. During a routine unloading operation, a Veolia employee was using a forklift to remove a pallet from a trailer when the forklift's forks accidentally punctured a drum positioned behind the pallet being unloaded. As a result of this incident, less than one gallon of waste flammable liquid was released from the punctured drum. Immediate action was taken to address the situation by promptly overpacking the damaged drum to prevent further leakage. Hazmat-trained Veolia employees conducted a thorough remediation of the spilled material. The swift response and proper handling of the situation by trained personnel ensured that the environmental impact was minimized and safety protocols were followed.
column170: The Veolia employee will be retrained in forklift operation focusing on specifically on spatial awareness, line of sight, and hazard recognition.

Upon arrival into the plant gate, he pulled over and discovered that the ammonia vapor was leaking out of the PRV.  He then  pulled the truck and trailer into our plant and shut the gates.  From there we dispatched (2) additional trucks from Granite City IL to remove the contents from the trailer.  At appox 0500 on Oct 22nd all ammonia was removed from the leaking trailer.   The trailer was then transported to our maintenance vendor.  They entered the tank and saw that a baffle had broken inside the tank and rested against the PRV and bending it causing it leak.
column170: At this time, we are still working with our maintenance vendor to determine if there are any long term solutions that could be put in place.

column169: An Engineering crew was working on a track next to track 22 (containing several Marathon Petroleum tank cars) in the West Colton rail yard, when they noticed a smell of propane. It was reported and I was dispatched. The entire cut of tank cars was inspected and CBTX 787961 was found to be leaking from the sample line with a hydrate forming around the plug, the hydrate was rinse off the valve was in the closed position, I attempted to tighten the valve, but it was closed, product is leaking past the valve. As the plug was being removed the release increased and did not slow down. The plug feeling like it may be cross threaded. With no way to address the release a midland kit was applied to the tank car. Tank car is scheduled to be transferred.
column170: Spoke with shipper about inspecting tank cars and proper securement.

column169: During a routine vehicle inspection at the job site, Veolia employees discovered paint dripping from a drum. Upon investigation, they determined that the leaking drum had been collected from a previous customer, Hentzen. The employees located the source of the leak, which was coming from the top of the drum.  After a thorough inspection, the seal was identified as the cause of the problem. The employees theorized that the truck's vibration during transport had caused the paint to seep through the faulty top seal. Fortunately, the spill was contained within the truck, and no paint had leaked outside while the vehicle was in motion.  The team took immediate action to address the situation. They contained the spill and overpacked the drum, along with all materials used in the cleanup process. This prompt response ensured that the incident was managed efficiently and safely, minimizing any potential environmental impact or further complications.
column170: Prior to filling, it is essential for customers to thoroughly examine all containers, including their gaskets and seals. Any containers found to have defective components should be immediately removed from circulation and not used for waste transportation or overpacked prior to shipment. This proactive approach to container inspection is crucial for ensuring safe and compliant waste handling during road transport.

ODOT Hazmat Inspector C. Kuenzi found the CBTX 725571 with wetness on top of the BOV cap threads.  The car was isolated and BNSF contracted Graymar Env to respond and inspect the car.  The cap was found in a tool tight condition and valve was fully closed.  The cap was removed and styrene was found inside the cap and on the threads.  The responders cleaned and inspected the gasket and applied teflon tape on the nozzle threads and reinstalled the cap.  There was no release to the ground, all styrene residue remained on the car.  The shipper was notified to apply for an OTMA to allow the car to continue in transportation to be offloaded and inspected further for possible repairs to the BOV and cap.

column169: 1. E-2024110325 Aircraft landed at Ralph Wien Memorial Airport in Kotzebue Alaska. After the offload, the Loadmaster walked the freight slated for upload. Lynden Air Cargo's ground handler FBX handles multiple different air carriers, and consolidated freight from three different customers. In which two of the customers freight was slated for another air carrier mixed in with the scheduled freight for Lynden Air Cargo. The Loadmaster failed to recognize the additional cargo and therefore did not notice the additional hazardous materials. The consolidated cargo was then loaded and then flown back to Ted Stevens Anchorage Airport to Lynden Air Cargo's facility. On September 18th Lynden Air Cargo was getting the shipment ready to be transported over the road to the one customer that was the only shipper we were aware of. During that phase the extra hazmat and pieces were identified, and an internal investigation ensued.   2. XPO Logistics terminal LDA experienced a UN2051 Nalco 1606A release from (3) 275-gallon poly totes. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct onsite cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 8 ounces of product released from the caps of all three totes. The caps on the totes were loose, resulting in material sloshing out in transit. The material impacted the tops of the totes and a 3” x 3” area of plywood in the trailer. The caps were tightened, and a slosh test was conducted on the totes to ensure there would not be further release. The impacted plywood, pads, and PPE were then containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: At 1907 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at XUR. It was reported that approximately 1 ounce of Potassium perchlorate released from a 50-pound plastic bag due to improper loading by the shipper. The bag has a rip in it and is still wrapped on the pallet. The release impacted trailer #4633605 at dock door 14.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-ounces of Potassium Perchlorate product released to a 1x1’ area of the trailer floor due to bag being overfilled and excess product leaking from seam.  They added cardboard bracing behind shrink-wrap to the area which had the release underneath, to add as extra layer of protection.  The contractors containerized floor sweepings of product into (1) 55-gallon metal drum (with vented  bung caps). The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On 10/1/2024 a Southeastern Freight Lines BTR associate was attempting to load 6 totes on pro# 374199108 into trailer 537530, located in dock door 58. At approximately 05:50, during the loading process, one of the placard/label frames on one of the totes caught the wall. The label frame was bent, ripped off of the tote, and punctured the 275-gallon tote. The tote immediately started Ieaking from the side. Approximately 10-gallons leaked inside of the trailer& on the dock. The tote was manuvered immediately& containment measures were performed to assure no further Ieakage. None of the chemical(UN3264) spilled onto the ground, or near water/drainage systems. Southeastern Freight Lines Safety was contacted at approximately 06:00. Safety contacted Hazmat 1, and Hazmat 1 contacted E3/OMI Environmental Services. Louisiana State Police arrived at approximately 08:00. E3/OMI arrived at approximately 09:00. Transfer& clean up procedures concluded at approximately 13:20. E3/OMI will return once approval has been received to retrieve for disposal the following: 1- Full tote(UN3264) 2- Empty Totes(Non-Hazardous/Residue)' 1- 55-Gallon Drum(Non-Hazardous)
column170: Please note the associate involved will go through a refresher training on proper handling of bulk Iiquids. We must handle all bulk& hazardous shipments with extra care in order to help mitigate events such as this one.

On 10/01/2024, at 0823 hours, personnel at the CSXT Selkirk, NY yard reported DOWX 74341, a loaded tank car containing Combustible liquids N.O.S. (Diethylene Glycol Monoethyl Ether), leaking from bottom of the tank car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Union Carbide, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2024-10-01-00216). HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found two of the eight bolts bottom outlet mounting flange bolts were less than tool tight. HEPACO inspected the bottom outlet valve to ensure there were no additional defects and secured all of the bolts tool tight to stop the release. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Bryan Hopkins Ph# 989-636-1483).  The car was held out of transportation pending further work and movement to home shop for a certified repair.

column169: AT THE UPS WORLDPORT FACILITY IN LOUISVILLE, KENTUCKY, ONE AIR PACKAGE WAS GIVEN TO A RESPONDER FOR CONTENT INSPECTION. THIS PACKAGE HAS NOT BEEN ACCEPTED FOR AIR OR TRANSPORTED IN THE AIR BY UNITED PARCEL SERVICE CO.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED BY A NIGHT SUPERVISOR AND BROUGHT TO CAGE. RESPONDER ASSESSED THE PACKAGE NOTING WET AREAS ON THE EXTERIOR OF THE BOX. UPON OPENING THE PACKAGE THE CONTENTS WERE LEAKING FROM THE LID. RESPONDER FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND OPERATORS QUICK REFERENCE GUIDE TO PROCESS THE CONTENTS.

As reported by Univar Operations Manager ..... .  "Ross Transportation Services arrived at the Dayton branch to transport waste to Ross from Dayton. When the warehouse worker inspected the trailer to load he found liquid on the floor of the trailer. At the time there was no waste leaking from the trailer. The Ross driver was advised of the leaker and asked to pull out of the dock into the truck lot where we placed containment under the trailer to keep any of the waste from reaching the ground. At this point we have not determined which container is leaking for sure but believe it to by a flammable hazardous waste that is contained in a .275 gallon tote. It appears to be a very slow leak since none is escaping the trailer and the floor does not showing signs of significant leaking. Four totes of the same profile are loaded onto the rear of the Ross trailer. NRC was contacted for emergency response to handle the leaker and any clean up required. The ETA for the clean up contractor is 3:00 pm ET. There has been no exposure of employees nor any release to the ground.   ER crew arrived on site and we determined the leaker was actually a DM of profile E80-9351A RIS which is a hazardous waste which is a flammable liquid, toxic and corrosive. It looks like less than a gallon escaped onto the trailer floor. The drum had a hole in the lower portion of the side of the drum which was allowing a very slow leak of the contents. The crew overpacked the drum using an overpack from Dayton branch. They used floor dry to clean up the trailer floor and placed the floor dry in the overpack with the drum. The overpack was labeled and loaded Back on the Ross trailer. The Dayton customer waste is being loaded onto the Ross trailer for shipment to Ross."
column170: Details have been forwarded back to the Univar Facility in Charlotte for them to identify the cause of the hole in the drum.

At 11:21 AM ET, ULA contacted the call center to report a spill that was found on the dock in Santa Fe Springs, CA. The spill consists of approximately 10 ounces of Potassium Chlorate, which released from 2–50-pound paper bags due to the pallet containing a total of 40-to-50-pound paper bags of the same property found tipped over. The terminal stated they will have to restack the pallet and there could potentially be other bags that are leaking.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-ounces from 3-damaged bags of product released to trailer floor and adjacent product due to improper loading. The contractors overpacked bags of product, plastic shrink-wrap, PPE, and floor debris submerged in water to (2) 15-gallon metal drums and (1) 5-gallon metal drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column43: HYDROFLUORIC ACID, WITH NOT MORE THAN 60 PERCENT STRENGTH
column169: On October 7, Veolia employees were collecting drums from the customer's site. To create space for additional drums in Veolia's truck, a Veolia employee began stacking empty 55 gallon containers that were already loaded in the truck. The Veolia employee misjudged the weight of one drum, assuming it contained residual waste when it actually weighed approximately 60 pounds. As a result, the drum slipped out of his hands, fell, and was punctured at the bottom when it struck a metal panel attached to the truck. Approximately 1 liter of fluid spilled from the drum. Spill pads were immediately placed to contain the spill and the spill was reported internally to request additional personnel to assist with the cleanup. At approximately 2:30PM (estimate), additional Veolia employees arrived to apply a hydrofluoric acid eater to the spill area along with the necessary PPE for proper management.  No spill was released outside of the truck.
column170: Veolia will implement the following corrective actions:  1. Conduct refresher training sessions with employees on proper container weight assessment procedures before handling.  2. Reinforce the importance of performing thorough routine inspections to:    - Verify container security    - Identify potential hazards  3. Reemphasize company policy prohibiting the double stacking of containers containing free liquids.  All affected employees have been notified of these requirements and will receive the necessary training and documentation.

column169: During a routine inspection at Veolia's ten day in-transit facility in Philadelphia, PA, Veolia staff discovered a compromised container. Upon investigation, they found that inner packages had leaked through three outer containers and were generating heat through a chemical reaction with the absorbent material present. It was determined that 5 x 1 gallon inner packages in each of the three containers were not upright and had leaked through vented caps onto an absorbent. It was further determined the absorbent utilized by the shipper contained organic material which resulted in the reaction and heat generation. The material was repackaged with all inner packages up right and placed in individual plastic bags with inorganic cushioning and absorbent to prevent any reaction resulting in three 55 gallon drums and one 30 gallon drum. The original absorbent material was wetted, placed into containers and transported for disposal along with the repackaged packages.
column170: The shipper was informed of the incident and was requested to retrain their personnel. Moving forward, when picking up  waste containers from the shipper, Veolia should either package the material on behalf of the customer or thoroughly inspect each inner package prior to packaging for shipment.

column169: CTMV was stopped at traffic signal on Navaho Road. When the light turned green, the operator began accelerating to make 90 degree left tum onto Fletcher Parkway. The tum is an"off-camber turn" as the outer tum radius surface is lower than the inner tum radius. The driver failed to respond correctly to this surface condition. As the CTMV turned, the liquid cargo surged to the passenger side of the cargo compartments. The sudden weight shift caused the CTMV to roll over to the right. The CTMV rotated 180 degrees clockwise and came to rest upside down straddling the roadway and sidewalk. Fuel began Ieaking through the venting devices mounted between the rollover rails on the top of the semi-trailer. The fuel flowed downhill along the sidewalk and curb. Fuel entered two storm drain entry points before the entry points were closed by sand bagging. The storm drain was dry down stream. While upside down, the compartments were tapped, and approximately 400 gallons were recovered from the compartments. Fuel recovery and remediation steps were begun immediately. Approximately 1500 gallons were recovered from a concrete utility pit located within the sidewalk underneath the upside down CTMV. The remaining fuel is being recovered by cleaning the storm drain conduit and replacing soil that has absorbed fuel downstream from the spill site. Asphalt roadway surface is being replaced for approximately 200 feet downhill from the spill site. The fuel did not enter any waterway.
column170: will be given on CTMV stability during turning maneuvers and off-camber roadways. This event was captured by our onboard camera system. The video will be shown to all CTMV operators during upcoming safety meetings with additional emphasis on selecting proper entry speed when making turns.

column169: Driver after crossing a rough portion of I-85 noticed a mist in his mirror. He subsequently stopped as soon as possible pulling off the roadway, and off the shoulder as well to investigate. Noticed product Leaking from the rear of his trailer(approx 1/2 gal per min). He placed the absorbent pads he had, to catch what he could and notified his supervisor. His supervisor immediately notified TWC regulatory dept. We then determined what was Leaking and reached out to our response company whom notified DHEC and located a company who could respond. We decided to send personnel from our Spartanburg facility with more pads and catch containers. They arrived before the response company and were able to move some material around on the trailer and where able to close the valve on the IBC and re-secure the dust cap on the tote. They then started using pads to absorb what product they could, as DHEC and the Response company arrived. They then took over assessing the impact and cleanup of the lost material.
column170: We sent an email to all Managers to remind all their team members-- those that fill IBCs, Load Trucks and Drivers to make sure all IBC valves are fully closed and dust caps are secure. Other actions are under consideration.

column169: Mindy Smith Operations Supervisor called safety to report a spill in trailer 85389, UN3264, CORROSIVE LIQUID ACIDICINORGANIC N.O .S., 8, PG II,. Mindy stated the freight looked to have been loaded in the nose of the trailer incorrectly and the bottom of the box was damaged causing one 1 gallon pail to spill on the trailer and other freight. Mindy stated it looked to be around 64oz of the product had spilled from the nose of the trailer on to the concrete on the ground in front of the dock door 11. Mindy stated the pallet was moved from the nose of the trailer to the door to take a better look at the box and the pail that spilled. Mindy stated the spill happened in transit and looks to have had other freight damage the box with the 1 gallon pail. Mindy stated after looking at the pail it looked to have spilled 1 gallon from the 1 gallon pail on the trailer floor, other freight and the gro und (concrete) outside the dock door 11. Mindy asked if the crew could unload the rest of the trailer and wipe off the spill that was on the other freight. Safety advised Mindy to stop work on the trailer and wait for a cleaning crew to assist with the cleaning of the freight, trailer floor and the ground outside the dock door. Mindy stated no water ways or drains are affected by the spill. The box slipped between the pallet boards and the forks of a forklift appear to have slit one of the gallon pail of product in the box.

On 10/02/2024 drums were picked up from Univar Solutions Norcross facility and delivered to Univar Solutions in Chattanooga. When arriving in Chattanooga the supervisor at the plant noticed a small amount of product coming out of the trailer towards the nose. When opening the door there was one drum of 40 discovered to be leaking. Hepaco was called on site and maintained/handled the cleanup. It was discovered that a drum was punctured by a nail on a pallet losing approximately 3301bs of sodium bisulfite. It looked like the drum may have shifted slightly and hit the nail. When leaving Norcross there were not any issues or signs of damage to the drum.
column170: After the incident we had an internal investigation and will begin using an extra strap on drums to prevent any kind of movement. We also have contacted our pallet supplier to discuss expectations on pallet condition and making sure nails are driven into pallets properly. This is something Univar does regularly and have not had any previous issues.

column169: Veolia employees were performing quality control checks in the warehouse at Veolia's ten day intransit facility when they noticed a 4G lab pack box was leaking a bright blue-green material. They immediately notified their supervisor, and the material was identified as "UN2586 Aryl Sulfonic Acids, Liquid with Not More than 5% Free Sulfuric Acid (4-Dodecylbenzenesulfonic Acid), 8, III." Approximately <= 10 mL of free liquids had leaked onto the warehouse floor.  The team immediately overpacked the material and used vermiculite absorbent to clean up residual liquids from the floor. After reviewing the incident, two conditions leading to the spill were discovered:  1.) A small cut in the inner liner near the top of the bag was discovered. Veolia believes this was caused during the initial packaging process or after someone reopened the box with a safety blade. This allowed for vermiculite absorbent and free liquids to escape the liner and leak into the box interior.  2.) The bottom of the box was not sealed properly; the middle seam was taped as required, but the side seams were left untaped, which allowed an easier pathway for the interior fluid to escape.
column170: The local Veolia management team will review proper packaging guidelines for this type of container and will ensure that all field teams are fully trained in the proper use and closure methods of these containers.

column169: On October 16, 2024, at Eli Lilly's Boston facility, Veolia employees were in the process of loading drums onto a truck when they detected a solvent odor. Initially, they attributed the smell to recently filled drums. However, upon relocating the vehicle, they discovered a pinhole leak in the top of one drum, just below the upper chime.  The affected container was a 55-gallon plastic drum, and it is believed that the puncture occurred during its removal from the storage location. Upon discovering the leak, employees promptly reported the incident and transferred the leaking drum into an 851A2 salvage drum to ensure safe transportation to the final disposal facility.  Approximately one pint of halogenated solvent waste escaped from the drum. The spill was quickly contained using spill pads and absorbent materials. The leaking drum, along with the cleanup materials, was then placed into an appropriate salvage drum.  Given the small size of the hole and the rapid response of the team, the release is estimated to have lasted about 10 minutes. The drum was still largely full when the leak was detected, and the quantity released did not exceed the reportable quantity (RQ) threshold.
column170: Following the incident on October 16, 2024, the Veolia safety manager was promptly informed. A subsequent investigation revealed that the drum in question had been provided by the customer. It is believed that the pinhole was present in the drum at the time of its acquisition.  The investigation concluded that human error did not directly contribute to the cause of the leak. The only oversight was the initial failure to detect the existing damage during the preliminary inspection.  As a result of this incident, both Veolia employees and the customer have committed to implementing more rigorous inspection protocols. Moving forward, there will be an increased emphasis on thoroughly examining drums for any signs of damage or potential leaks before handling or transport. This enhanced vigilance aims to prevent similar incidents in the future and improve overall safety practices.

column169: On 10/9/2024 at around 12:00, CPKC Hazmat was made aware by FRA Inspector Vincent Leishman that NATX 37675 had been found Ieaking from the bottom outlet valve secondary closure cap during a hazmat inspection. CPKC mobilized a railroad qualified response contractor to investigate and mitigate the release. Upon arrival, responders actuated the bottom outlet valve in an attempt to secure it prior to removing the bottom outlet valve(BOV) cap. While removing the BOV cap, responders discovered that it was less than tool tight. Additionally, responders noticed that Methanol was Ieaking past the bottom outlet ball and seal. A new gasket was installed in the BOV cap. The BOV cap was then secured tool tight, stopping the release. File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
column170: to conduct thorough inspections prior to movement in order to reduce valve failures in the field. Non Accidental Releases(NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases(a.k.a. package closure Issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a rookause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with SOO Line Railroad(Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Ed Dankbar, SOO Line Railroad, 120 S 6th ST STE 900, Minneapolis, MN 55402. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

On Tuesday, 10/22/2024 at approximately 11:30 a train crew reported UTLX 202686 leaking from the top of the tank car. UTLX 202686 was a loaded tank car of Acetone from the Advansix Plant in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. Conrail Hazardous Material Manager, Joe Caaccamo was in the yard and responded to inspect the tank car. Upon inspection  liquid was visible coming from the breadbox seal number ADVANSIX 074737 was intact on the breadbox. The seal was removed and the liquid line was found in the open position well as the secondary securement plug less than tool tight. Once the valve was placed in the closed position the leak stopped entirely. The secondary securement plug was properly secured and all material was dissipating/evaporating from the tank car. Seal number ULINE 1202402 was placed on the breadbox. The tank car was ppaced to be inspected prior to release pending OTMA the following day with no leak detected on 10/23/2024. Tank car UTLX 202686 is still pending OTMA in the Pavonia Terminal. Jeff Matlack with Advansix (267) 319-6382 was informed of the situation and advised OTMA is required.

On 10/9/24, a drum from SD Myers was delivered to Veolia's ten-day in-transit facility and temporarily placed on the dock pending transfer to another trailer for final disposal. During the subsequent loading process for outbound transportation, facility personnel observed liquid on the floor near the drum's location.  Upon investigation, it was discovered that a pinhole in the bottom chime of the drum had allowed its contents to leak. To address this issue, the following actions were taken:  1. The compromised drum was immediately overpacked to ensure safe continued transportation. 2. The affected concrete surface was thoroughly decontaminated in full compliance with the procedures outlined in 40 CFR § 761.79(b)(4).  These prompt actions ensured the containment of the spill, the safe handling of the drum, and the proper remediation of the affected area, all in accordance with applicable regulations and safety protocols.
column170: To prevent similar incidents in the future, the following corrective actions have been implemented:   1. Pre-Transport Inspection: Veolia field employees were reminded to perform a rigorous inspection of all drums before they are removed from the customer's site. This includes a thorough visual and physical check of each drum, with particular attention to the bottom chime and other potential weak points.  2. Secondary Inspection at 10-Day Facility: Upon arrival at the 10-Day facility, all drums will undergo a second comprehensive inspection before being placed in the storage area. This double-check process aims to identify any damages or potential leaks that may have been overlooked or occurred during transit.  These measures are designed to reduce the risk of accepting or handling compromised drums, thereby enhancing overall safety and transportation and environmental compliance.

On October 15th 2024 between the hours of 13:00 and 14:00 the driver loaded 7,500 gallons of clear diesel fuel into truck number 60,  trailer number 139 at the Kinder Morgan fuel Terminal in North Augusta, SC. The driver left Kinder Morgan headed towards Columbia on I-20 and got off the interstate on exit 22 which is HWY #1. The driver traveled down #1 Hwy until he got to Chinquapin Road in Monetta and turned right. Chinquapin Rd turned into Two Notch Road which is in Leesville SC. The driver made a right turn onto Pond Branch and proceeded towards exit 44. The driver came over the bridge slowing down so that he would be able to make the turn. The driver stated he didn’t feel like he was speeding making the turn, but he never looked at the speedometer. The driver made his turn, and the truck proceeded to lay over on its side. The Lexington County Fire Service responded to the scene. The rollover resulted in approximately 1500 gallons of ULSD being released on to the ground. The spilt fuel was recovered/remediated by Republic Services. The remaining product was pumped from the rolled over trailer to a trailer brought on scene by Barnes Oil & Propane Representatives.
column170: All CDL drivers will immediately be retrained in Cargo Tank Rollover prevention techniques and the effects of liquid sloshing.

column169: On 10/9/24, at 04:37 personnel in the CSXT Radnor discovered SHPX221329, a residue tank car of Butadiene, leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, BASF, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2024-1009-00030). Marion Environmental Inc. (MEI), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the B-end liquid valve partially open and the Drylok-style secondary securement not containing the release. Contractor personnel closed the valve and stopped the release.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative (Scott McDonald, 409 981-5133).  The car was subsequently held at Radnor Yard until the secondary closure was replaced and an OTMA-1 was submitted and approved by the FRA.

column169: On 10/14/2024 at approximately 1530, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 475356 at the ramp faclity in Middletown, reporting undeclared dangerous goods.  This is a multiple piece shipment that consists of 6 fiberboard boxes, each containing one  44 lb. bag of pigment .  One of the labels on the outer packages identifies the inner contents as "DCL Quindo Magenta" and displays a GHS corrosive mark.  Dangerous Goods Administration acquired an online safety data sheet, which classified the commodity as UN 1263 Paint.  Further inspection of the packages confirmed this classification.  None of the packages displayed the required markings, labeling, packaging and paperwork that were in accordance with IATA Regulations.  The shipment is being held for an FAA investigation.  UPDATE: After attaining a safety data sheet from the shipper, it had been confirmed that this commodity classified as a nonhazardous shipment.

The impacted absorbents were then containerized into a 55-gallon metal drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: On October 29, 2024, at 1513 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Albuquerque, NM regarding the release of corrosive fryer & grill cleaner. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 1 cup of Keystone Fryer & Grill Cleaner (UN1824, 8, II) from (1) 1-gallon jug into the carboard box that it was contained in. The release was reportedly due to a load shift, impacting the carboard along with other jugs of product in the box. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. The release was cleaned up with the proper PPE. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (1) 5-gallon DF, which was then taken offsite by the contractor for proper disposal. All salvaged product was packaged in (1) 55-gallon DM and kept by the client per instruction.

column163: VICE PRESIDENT OF SAFETY AND COMPLIANCE
column169: Driver allowed CTMV to drift onto the right shoulder of the roadway.  The driver over corrected to the left, which caused the CTMV to roll onto its right side.  This caused about a 2 to 3 foot cut into the tank.  Approximately 3,500 gallons of unleaded gasoline spilled onto the shoulder of the roadway.  The Texas Department of Public Safety responded to the scene and notified United Petroleum Transports, Inc.  UPT then contracted an Environmental Clean up Service.  The Environmental Clean up Service went the scene and contained the spill.  It the went through the process of removing the contaminated soil and replacing it with clean soil.  The final remediation was done on 11/11/2024 and report was sent to TXDEQ.  Fortunately, the spill occurred in an unpopulated area so no people, homes, or business were affected.
column170: We feel the tanker did its job protecting the fuel and only allowed a portion of the load to spill out.  This incident was caused by driver error and not the failure of the package.

column169: Aircraft landed at Ralph Wien Memorial Airport in Kotzebue Alaska. After the offload, the Loadmaster walked the freight slated for upload. Lynden Air Cargo's ground handler FBX handles multiple different air carriers, and consolidated freight from three different customers. In which two of the customers freight was slated for another air carrier mixed in with the scheduled freight for Lynden Air Cargo. The Loadmaster failed to recognize the additional cargo and therefore did not notice the additional hazardous materials. The consolidated cargo was then loaded and then flown back to Ted Stevens Anchorage Airport to Lynden Air Cargo's facility. On September 18th Lynden Air Cargo was getting the shipment ready to be transported over the road to the one customer that was the only shipper we were aware of. During that phase the extra hazmat and pieces were identified, and an internal investigation ensued.
column170: - Add additional face to face training requirement to LM2 - Hazardous Material Training Module for extra detail to finding undeclared hazmat, proper use of hazmat checklist, flight verification procedures outside of Anchorage.   - Outstation Procedure manual revisions to include preliminary backhaul verification against hazardous shipping papers for the Loadmaster to review and accept.

column169: On 10/8/2024 at 12:15 PM, CPKC Hazmat became aware that residue SODIUM CHLORATE hopper car, OFOX 60804, was Ieaking while in the ST Paul, MN rail yard. A rail qualified response contractor was mobilized to investigate and mitigate the release. Upon arrival, OFOX 60804 was found to be Ieaking from the A end hopper on the left side at the bottom camlock cap fitting. The A end hopper was found to have less than 1/8 of a compartment of liquid and solid solution. OFOX 60804 was also found to be Ieaking from the B end hopper on the left side where the bottom of the hopper is fastened to the frame of the car. The B end hopper was found with over 1/2 of a compartment of liquid and solid solution. It appeared that the shipper failed to fully unload the hoppers before releasing the car into transportation. Estimated release from the A end hopper is 9 gallons. Estimated release from the B end hopper is 1 gallon. Responders stopped the release from the A end hopper by securing a nitrile glove over the camlock cap fitting and the loading/unloading line with duct tape and a tension strap. Containment was placed under the point of release emanating from the B end hopper and sealant was applied to the seam where the bottom of the hopper is fastened to the frame of the car to stop the leak. The source of the B end hopper release was.inside the hopper and could not be accessed. The contents of OFOX 60804 were transferred Into a tank truck, and then the hoppers were rinsed with water. The root defect was not determined for the A end bottom camlock cap fitting, though it was thought to have been attributable to a loose component. Likewise, the source of the release on the B end was not determined because it was not visible; however, due to the nature of the commodity moved in this specialized hopper car, it is likely to be attributable·to a failure in a weld or seam within the hopper. File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best info,„iation available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
column170: The SOO LINE RAILROAD COMPANY(DBA CPKC) notified shipper of this release. Continued emphasis with Offerors/Shippers is made to conduct thorough inspections prior to movement in order to reduce valve failures in the field. Non Accidental Releases(NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases(a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with SOO Line Railroad(Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Ed Dankbar, SOO Line Railroad, 120 S 6th ST STE 900, Minneapolis, MN 55402. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

On 10-24-2024 at approximately 07:00 AM a CN transportation employee observed a white vapor emitting from the top of tank car # RCRX 2542 (residue/UN 1789/Class 8/PGII) while performing switching operations at the CN Mays Yard in Harahan, LA. The car was set out to an isolation track. All departments were notified leading to an emergency response from a CN Dangerous Goods Team contractor. The responding contractor observed a small amount of liquid (PH tested ?1?) within the protective housing. All securement nuts on the air and liquid valve were verified to be tool tight. There was no obvious point of the leak during the initial inspection. The tank car was pressurized with dry air to 10 psi for the purpose of identifying the exact origin of the leak. The pressure test revealed a minuscule leak emanating from the spool of the liquid eduction line through what appeared to be a pin sized hole. The tank car was completely de-pressurized through a scrubbing media. The pinhole on the spool was wrapped with chemical tape to prevent any further leakage. The car owner was notified of the findings and will send a qualified mobile repair unit out to replace the spool and re-qualify the tank car. 10-31-2024 the tank car owner performed an assessment of the tank car. Below is their findings: Technicians from our Saint Gabreil, LA certified shop responded to RCRX 2542 on 10/31/2024.  Upon arrival, the technician's initial inspection found product residue inside the protective housing.  In addition, there appeared to be no gasket present below the product blind flange which was confirmed after removing the blind flange.  A product gasket was applied and secured.  The car was then pressurized to 30 psi and a certified leak test was performed to all fittings and connections with no leaks found.   The residue product was rinsed off of the fittings and side of car.  Security seals were applied as well to the fittings.

column169: S&L Company Transport driver started his workday at 1753 on 9/31/2024. He drove from his parking location at 15222 Hudson Ave., Spring Hill, FL to the Orlando, FL terminal to load his truck. He made two deliveries - the first being in Palmetto, FL at an AmeriGas facility, and the last being in Clearwater a the AmeriGas facility. When Transport Driver completed the final delivery in Clearwater, he drove back to his parking location at 15222 Hudson Ave., Spring Hill, FL, which is an AmeriGas property.   To access this location, the Transport Driver backs in off the roadway to get into the yard. On this morning at 0522, he pulled up headed westbound on Hudson Ave. and began his backing maneuver traveling 3 mph. He was across both lanes of traffic in the middle of his maneuver when a 3rd party vehicle traveling eastbound on Hudson Ave. crashed into the transport trailer. The Transport Driver immediately got out of the vehicle to assess the situation and called 911.   When emergency personnel arrived on scene, the scene was secured and the leak was assessed. There was a small leak coming from the flange of the pump under the transport and emergency personnel and AmeriGas decided it would be best to evacuate the remaining propane in the transport by flaring it off. The responding fire dept. utilized water spray to dissipate some of the propane vapor under the transport before they were able to flare. The leak lasted for roughly 2 hours before flaring equipment could be set up and utilized. The flare was set up and remaining propane was burnt off prior to the transport and 3rd party vehicle being moved and the road re-opened.
column170: AmeriGas is reassessing this parking location for our transport truck. AmeriGas will be looking for off site parking that will allow for our driver to not have to back off of a roadway in order to access the property and park.

column169: Dayton Freight personnel observed approximately one (1) gallon of Metalux 9225 Silver Quartz paint released from a carton containing four (4) one (1) gallon metal cans due to improper loading. Personnel advised the release impacted the skid and the cardboard only. No storm drains or waterways were reported to be impacted by the release. Dayton Freight personnel advised they cleaned the release and generated one (1) thirty (30) gallon poly drum of waste containing the carton along with the four (4) damaged one (1) gallon metal cans. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location. The generated waste will remain onsite for Dayton Freight’s contracted hazardous waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

On 10/04/2024, at 2007 hours, personnel at the CSXT Avon, Indiana Yard discovered RDRX 300969, a covered hopper car load of Hazardous Waste, Solid, NOS, leaking from a bottom unloading valve. The car was isolated and the shipper, Blanchard Refining, was of the incident. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found liquid leaking at the threaded connected between the bottom unloading piping and the unloading valve of the hopper car.  Contractor personnel tightened the connection between the valve and the car’s piping which stopped the release. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Jennifer Johnson (209-986-1196). Following securement of the release the car was released.

column169: At 10:50 AM ET, XSJ contacted ERTS to notify of a spill that was found inside of a trailer in Marshfield, MO. The spill consists of approximately 5 or more gallons of Flurospar White, which released from (1) 275-gallon metal tote due to a missing lid, causing the tote to slosh and splash during transit. Contractors confirmed 1-gallon of material had been released and transferred into a 330-gallon plastic tote.  The old tote was cleaned and wiped down, released material was cleaned up on the trailer floor and walls and the waste material, impacted granular absorbents, pads, PPE, plastic and PVC tube were placed into (1) 55-gallon metal drum.  The waste was staged on site for terminal to manage.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal LAB experience a battery acid release from a 2400-pound UN2794, Battery, Wet, Filled with Acid. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-gallons of product released to a 23’ x 8’ area of the trailer floor and a 30’ x 10’ area of the concrete lot below. The battery was not properly secured and fell over as a result, resulting in acid releasing from the caps and breaking the pallet. The battery was up righted and resecured for shipment on. Absorbents and soda ash were deployed to clean and neutralize the impacted areas. All impacted absorbents, impacted pallet wood, poly, and cleanup debris were then containerized into (2) 55-gallon, a 25-gallon, and a 30-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On 10/18/2024, a World Fuel Service, Inc. (WFS) transport driver when starting their shift at 04:30 called the HSE Manager to report a spill at the WFS Milford Bulk Plant. They reported there was diesel spilled throughout the facility yard and onto US HWY 50. The transport driver did know who caused it. They provided pictures and was allowed to start their shift. The HSE Manager and Milford Operations Manager went to the site to further investigate the release and its severity. After arriving to the Milford yard it was clear that someone had loaded a tank wagon and spilled product without notifying anyone. The HSE Manager and Operations Manager looked at unit 865 and it was clear the truck had an overfill and product had spilled over top of it. Th truck had fuel staining on the tanker and on the front/back of the it.  HSE and Operations spoke with both night drivers and confirmed who used unit 865. When speaking with driver that used 865, they stated that they did not know about or caused any spill. The driver had started their shift at 17:30 on 10/17/2024. Footage was pulled from the truck camera system in order to determine the cause of the release. Camera footage showed the driver loading from 06:00 pm to around 06:35 pm. Camera footage showed the driver causing a spill of diesel from the truck after loading. It showed the driver pulling out of the loading bay and then back in the loading bay spilling product. Next, the driver gets out to look at the truck top, then gets back in the truck and backs out of loading bay and pulls around circling in the yard. Then, parks 10 feet away from a storm drain at the facility while product is still being released to the ground from the truck top. Next, the driver gets out and looks at the spill. During this time the driver does not take any action to stop or slow the spill nor did they report it to HSE or Operations. The driver was not following procedures and neglected to take any actions addressing the spill. Finally, the driver walks into the office building, comes back out and proceeds to leave the yard. When doing so more diesel is spilled. The majority of diesel is spilled in the facility yard. The driver turns right (west) onto US HWY 50. Product splashes off the truck onto the road way for several hundred yards. The driver finished his shift, returned to the yard and parked the truck back at the Milford Facility without reporting the release.  Approximately 30 gallons of diesel fuel was spilled. HEPACO was contacted on 10/18/2024 at 04:57 and was dispatched to clean up the spill. One storm drain was impacted at the WFS facility and the diesel fuel was contained to the catch basin and recovered. Weather conditions were dry and there was no precipitation. On 10/18/2024 between 07:56 and 12:31 the NRC, Ohio EPA, Clermont Co. EMA, and Miami TWP Fire Dept. were notified of the spilled. Diesel that spilled on to US HWY 50 was not cleaned up and no roadway safety issues were reported. HEPACO finished the
column170: World Fuel Service, Inc. (WFS) reviews and investigates all incidents to determine root cause and what corrective actions need to be implemented to prevent any reoccurrences. The spill occurred because of a human error. The WFS driver overfilled one of the tanker truck compartments during loading and did not take any actions to report, contained, or mitigate the spill. Operations personnel will be briefed on the incident during the next safety meetings and on WFS spill reporting and response requirements.

column169: At 1612 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal XHG. It was reported that approximately 1 ounce of Vigil Quat released from a plastic tote due unknown cause. The terminal believes it may just be a loose cap, however due to the corrosive nature the SCM has requested a crew responded for clean-up and further assessment. The release impacted trailer # 5633416. No storm drains or waterways are reported to be impacted by the release. The contractor cleaned-up the release using absorbent pads and replaced cap on the tote. One 30-gallon DF containing the impacted absorbent pads and contractor PPE was generated and staged for waste disposal. XPO will manage any waste generated from spill responses.

On 10/11/2024 at approximately 1730, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 966383 and the station location in Ronkonkoma, reporting a dangerous goods spill.  The shipment is a large cylinder.  The shipment was reported to have fallen from the sort belt and began to make a "hissing" sound, indicating that the cylinder was releasing pressure.  After evaluation, the shipment was isolated from people and other freight until completely depressurized.  The shipment is being for customer pick-up.

column169: Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted an 8ft-by-15ft area of the trailer floor and concrete terminal floor and estimated that two (2) gallons of material was released due to the battery overturning during transit. Clean Harbors personnel deployed a neutralizer to the impacted area and then used a granular absorbent to recover the spent material. The spent absorbents were containerized into six (6) 55-gallon poly drums. The generated waste were transported to a nearby ESTES terminal. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

XPO Logistics terminal LTU experienced a UN2924 Silquest A-1101 Silane release from a 330-gallon metal tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct onsite cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 3 gallons of material released to a 10’ x 10’ area of the trailer floor due to a loose tote cap. The release impacted on the trailer floor, walls, ceiling, dunnage, and a poly tote in the trailer. Vinegar was utilized to clean and neutralize the impacted areas along with pads and oil dri. The cap was re-tightened on the tote and secured for shipment on. All impacted pads, absorbents, and cleanup debris were placed into 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
attachment Name:IMG_20241014_031011162_MP.jpg

On October 15, 2024, one (1) 1-gallon jug of UN1789 was crushed during unloading and released approximately six (6) ounces of product to the dock floor and cardboard box. R+L personnel utilized a fire extinguisher when they noticed smoke emerging from the box. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site.  FCE personnel discovered that all released Transchem Muriatic Acid (UN1789) had dried, on the impacted surfaces, due to the fire extinguisher being utilized by R+L personnel. Crews collected the damaged jug and the impacted cardboard box for disposal. FCE personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted areas and swept them in with hand tools. All waste was containerized in two (2) 55-gallon drums.

column169: When they attempted delivery at the consignee the trailer started leaking from an 8 bolt flange where the primary discharge pipe meets the secondary discharge piping.  After they shut down product flow and drained the piping the leak stopped.  We got it back to our repair center and tightened the bolts 2 rotations which fixed the leak.
column170: The trailer was new in 2023 and was almost to its yearly inspection timeframe.  This seems like a one off but we'll have to watch our newer trailers closely and see if we have any trends forming where we need to increase the inspection interval on this component

column63: Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Preparation for Transportation
column169: On October 24th, 2024, at 1818, personnel at the CSXT Avon, Indiana Yard reported a strong odor in the area TILX301735, a residue tank car of Liquefied Petroleum Gas.  The car was isolated and the shipper, DK Trading and Supply/Cenovus, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2024-1024-00183). HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car leaking from both liquid line valves and the vapor valve.  The cause of the releases was all valves being found partially open and secondary closures not secured “tool tight”.   Contractor personnel closed all valves, inspected and installed all secondary closures properly.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Stacy Myers (567-901-1941).

column169: While doing a warehouse inventory, cargo agent noticed a DGR pc of cargo looked wet. He contacted a supervisor for further Investigation. This pe was on top of a skid containing additional pcs of the awb. Upon removing this po from the top of the skid it was noticed that it was toxic. The area was roped off and the import file was obtained, the 24 hour emergency contact number (Chemtrek) was called. Agent fowarded the Safety Data Sheet. We were told to follow rule 6 and 7 which allowed us to place the fiberboard box into a salvage container using protective equipment. The box itself was not noticably leaking but did appear wet. Absorbant material was first placed into the container, then the box, then more abosorbant material.
column170: This peice was loaded on top of a skid and not properly secured. Staff briefed to ensure all peices on a skid are properly secured to prevent it from falling during movement of the skid. In addition, staff will be informed not to load skids at a height that exceeds the storage space. Responsible for incident person retake the DG training. Employee served a 6 day suspension, was re-trained, and will be monitored moving forward. A final warning was issued. Prior to this incident, the agent had a good safety record and has been a strong agent for the past 2 years he has been employed.

column169: Jesse Marquez-Zamora was traveling northbound on freeway 101 at 50 mph on 10-3-2024 at approximately 820am. The vehicle traveling in front of Jesse proceeded to heavy brake. Jesse then proceeded to apply his brakes, but it was not enough to stop his propane bobtail. Jesse then attempted to maneuver around the vehicle in front of him to the left, this was when Jesse lost control of the truck. Jesse's truck then proceeded to hit the vehicle in front of him and rolled 2 times, there were a total of 4 vehicles involved. During the rollover a piped valve was knocked off causing the release of approximately 2240 gallons of propane. Jesse and another individual were taken to the ER for evaluation then released
column170: We will complete daily, weekly and monthly driver reminders to be practicing the following safe driving techniques:  • Avoid Distraction o Do not talk on your cell phone while driving o Be aware of your surroundings while driving o Do not drive any vehicle under the influence of drugs or alcohol • Watch your Speed o Speed limits are there for a reason o Take your time and obey all traffic laws o Beware of deteriorating road conditions and know when to park the truck • Safe Following Distances o Keep a Safe Following distance between the vehicles in front of you o Do not tailgate vehicle  o You need to leave a minimum of 5 seconds between you and the vehicle in front of you • Practice Defensive Driving o Always stay focused and alert o Be aware of your surroundings o Avoid speeding o Always wear your seatbelt o Use extreme caution while switching lanes • Vehicle Maintenance o Complete your pre and post trip truck inspections ¿ Document any defects ¿ Have those defects properly repaired before the truck is placed back into service o Verify that your tires are properly inflated o Do not skip the required PM’s  ¿ PM allow the mechanics to complete and bumper to bumper inspection confirming your truck is in good condition • Use your Seatbelts o First and foremost, it is the law and our company policy o Your safety and the safety of our fellow drivers are the most important ¿ Seatbelts save lives, wearing it is not an option, it’s a requirement We will require that all drivers continue to complete reoccurring education on safe driving techniques.

column169: On October 5, 2024, at approximately 12:30 p.m in Roger Mills County, Oklahoma, a Plains transport driver with a load of crude oil traveling westbound on Oklahoma Highway 47 departed the roadway. The driver attempted to re-enter the roadway, causing both truck and cargo to roll 1 1/4 times before reentering the roadway where it overturned. The driver was found deceased on the scene.  Upon investigation, the front ladder of the cargo trailer had punctured a hole in the trailer at the 7 o'clock position (11 o'clock position upright). As a result of the rollover, approximately 140 barrels of crude oil were released into the dry roadside ditch. The vehicle was removed from the scene, and impacted soils were excavated and removed in accordance with the Oklahoma Corporation Commission Oil & Gas Division clean-up criteria.

column169: On October 4th during the PM sort a package was discovered that had a distinct sound of an aerosol can.   After calling DG Admin the station opened the package and found three cans of spray paint. There are no markings or labels on the outside of the package that indicates the package contains any dangerous goods, however a safety data sheet classifies these as UN1950, Aerosols, flammable, 2.1.  The package is being help pending investigation of the FAA.

column43: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column169: Package was completely destroyed. Package burned only thing left are 120 lithium battery cells. Undeclared package, no hazmat markings or labels no OP-900. Package was lithium batteries that were mishandled. The batteries failed and caught fire. Resulting in fumes/smoke and an evacuation that lasted around 25 minutes. The sort resumed after the fire department cleared the affected area. There are no markings or information  on this package left after the fire department put the fire out. was reported to NCR.

During sort operations at the MEMH location a fiberboard box was dropped during the loading process. The fiberboard box contained four glass bottles packaged with styrofoam holders top and bottom and packaged in plastic bags. One of the glass bottles broke spilling the contents inside of the fiberboard box. All contents were placed into a steel salvage package and a new declaration will be obtained for movement.
attachment Name:Hazmat- Damaged Haz Mat Package Disposition 04302024.pdf

RESPONDED TO A LEAKING AIR PACKAGE PREVIOUSLY FLOWN ON UPS AIRCRAFT. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS DISCOVERED TWO PLASTIC 15L CONTAINERS OF FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS. ONE PLASTIC CONTAINER IS MARKED AND LABELLED AS TOLUENE 99% WITH A UN NUMBER OF DIETHYL ETHER, UN1155, CLASS 3, PG II. SECOND BOTTLE IS LABELLED AS ISOPROPANOL 99%, UN1219, PG II. BOTH LEAKING FROM THEIR CLOSURES WITH APPROXIMATELY FIVE LITERS TOTAL LEAKING. THERE ARE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER BOX. THIS PACKAGE WAS DROPPED OFF IN NEW YORK USING UPS SHIPPER NUMBER KE7177, CLARITY CHEMICAL CORPORATION, 411 N EVANS CREEK RD, ROGUE RIVER OR 97537-4685.

column43: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column169: RESPONDED TO AN AIR PACKAGE DUE TO THE RATTLE OF AEROSOL CANS. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS DISCOVERED (4) 4 OUNCE AEROSOL CANS OF FLAMMABLE AVON SKIN SO SOFT INSECT REPELLENT. THERE ARE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER BOX. INVOICE AND THERMAL LABEL DESCRIPTION IS SUNTAN LOTION. THIS PACKAGE WAS SHIPPED FROM MASSACHUSETTS USING UPS ACCOUNT NUMBER 6VR107, FREIGHTCOM, 9220 BASS LAKE RD, MINNEAPOLIS MN 55428-3115. THIS PACKAGE HAS NOT BEEN ACCEPTED FOR AIR OR TRANSPORTED IN THE AIR BY UNITED PARCEL SERVICE CO.

The shipment was discovered by Security and held. The inner contents were clothing and perfume. the 2 bottles of perfume are not full and there was no evidence of a spill, however 1 bottle has a capacity of 80ml (Hypnotic Vanilla Parfum Zara) is 50% full. The second bottle, Zara Golden Decade, capacity 30 ml, only 25% full. The shipment is being held for FAA investigation.
